/*********************************************** JAVA **************************************************/

Optimal Solution - Use level-order traversal and record the last node at each level to obtain the binary tree’s right-side view.

class Solution {
    public List<Integer> rightSideView(TreeNode root) {
        // List to store the right-side view values
        List<Integer> res = new ArrayList<>();
        // Edge case: empty tree
        if (root == null)
            return res;
        // Queue for level-order (BFS) traversal
        Queue<TreeNode> que = new LinkedList<>();
        que.add(root);
        // Traverse the tree level by level
        while (!que.isEmpty()) {
            // Number of nodes at current level
            int size = que.size();
            int lastValue = 0; // Stores the last node value of this level
            // Process all nodes in the current level
            for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
                TreeNode node = que.poll();
                // Update lastValue — the last node processed will be the rightmost one
                lastValue = node.val;
                // Add left and right children for next level
                if (node.left != null)
                    que.offer(node.left);
                if (node.right != null)
                    que.offer(node.right);
            }
            // Add the rightmost value of the current level
            res.add(lastValue);
        }
        return res;
    }
}

Time Complexity :- O(N).
Space Complexity :- O(N).
